11
00:00:37,729 --> 00:00:40,842
Let me introduce first 
a few properties of the Sun.

12
00:00:41,901 --> 00:00:45,852
The solar distance from Earth is called 
the astronomical unit.

13
00:00:46,394 --> 00:00:50,593
It is approximately 1.5 on average 
10¹¹ meters.

14
00:00:51,614 --> 00:00:53,756
The astronomical unit

15
00:00:54,010 --> 00:00:56,997
is a basic unit in the solar system 
and even beyond.

16
00:00:57,579 --> 00:01:01,923
The mass of the sun, which is 
approximately 2 x 10³⁰ kilograms,

17
00:01:02,384 --> 00:01:06,457
is a typical value for a normal star,
and a normal star

18
00:01:06,457 --> 00:01:11,864
is an object that shines steadily 
for a fair long time by burning hydrogen.

19
00:01:12,743 --> 00:01:14,103
The Sun's radius,

20
00:01:14,502 --> 00:01:18,830
which is approximately 7 x 10⁸ meters

21
00:01:19,590 --> 00:01:24,835
is the radius of the visible disc
which, we notice is almost perfectly round.

22
00:01:25,257 --> 00:01:29,273
The diameter of the Sun is a little bit 
more than half a degree

23
00:01:29,273 --> 00:01:30,935
as we see it from Earth.

24
00:01:31,720 --> 00:01:35,467
Note that the shape of the Sun 
is extremely sharply defined

25
00:01:35,467 --> 00:01:38,501
because almost all the light 
we receive on earth

26
00:01:39,019 --> 00:01:43,938
originates in a thin layer, which is a few 
hundred kilometers thick, the photosphere.

27
00:01:44,757 --> 00:01:48,910
In fact, if we move from 
the center of the sun, going outwards,

28
00:01:48,910 --> 00:01:53,069
the matter changes rapidly 
from being almost completely opaque

29
00:01:53,592 --> 00:01:56,566
to almost completely transparent 
in the photosphere.

30
00:01:58,272 --> 00:02:01,433
The sun emits electromagnetic radiation

31
00:02:01,857 --> 00:02:09,264
and its luminosity is approximately 
3.84 x 10²⁶ watts.

32
00:02:09,800 --> 00:02:13,628
Using the famous E=mc² relation,

33
00:02:14,147 --> 00:02:20,509
this yields a mass loss of about 
4 x 10⁹ kilograms per second,

34
00:02:20,793 --> 00:02:25,125
which results in a negligible perturbation
to the total mass of the sun.

35
00:02:26,256 --> 00:02:30,327
And finally the elemental 
abundances of the Sun

36
00:02:30,327 --> 00:02:32,866
are typical for cosmic sources.

37
00:02:33,979 --> 00:02:36,855
The Sun is made approximately, in mass,

38
00:02:36,855 --> 00:02:42,211
by 73.4% of hydrogen, 25% of helium,

39
00:02:42,211 --> 00:02:47,706
and then 1.6% of everything else,
mostly metals.

40
00:02:49,440 --> 00:02:51,770
The Sun is a main sequence star.

41
00:02:51,770 --> 00:02:56,012
That is a star that has been shining 
steadily for a fair amount of time.

42
00:02:56,678 --> 00:03:00,117
The largest mass observed 
for a main sequence star

43
00:03:00,117 --> 00:03:04,966
is of the order of approximately 
100 times the mass of our Sun

44
00:03:05,443 --> 00:03:10,565
while the lower limit is slightly below 
0.1 times the mass of our Sun.

45
00:03:11,694 --> 00:03:14,647
An interesting property of 
main sequence stars is that

46
00:03:14,647 --> 00:03:17,168
they follow well-defined empirical laws.

47
00:03:17,720 --> 00:03:20,921
One such law is shown in this plot here

48
00:03:21,174 --> 00:03:25,612
where the star luminosity is shown 
as a function of the star mass.

49
00:03:27,053 --> 00:03:31,516
This is a logarithmic plot 
and we are using normalized units

50
00:03:31,516 --> 00:03:36,074
where the mass of the star
is normalized to the mass of our Sun

51
00:03:36,812 --> 00:03:40,962
and the luminosity normalized 
to its luminosity.

52
00:03:41,593 --> 00:03:45,515
In fact, this red dot here 
in the middle of the plot

53
00:03:46,221 --> 00:03:48,620
indicates the position of our Sun.

54
00:03:50,045 --> 00:03:53,901
If we now try to interpolate 
this data with a straight line,

55
00:03:56,508 --> 00:04:00,558
we observe an interesting property 
of a main sequence's star.

56
00:04:01,567 --> 00:04:03,354
The luminosity of the star

57
00:04:04,277 --> 00:04:07,940
is related to the mass of the star 
through a scaling law,

58
00:04:08,748 --> 00:04:14,876
where the exponent <i>α</i> varies 
between three and four.

59
00:04:17,258 --> 00:04:22,278
This is telling us that
the luminosity of the star increases

60
00:04:22,278 --> 00:04:24,867
much faster than the mass of the star.

61
00:04:25,138 --> 00:04:28,527
Let's see an important consequence 
of this scaling law.

62
00:04:28,950 --> 00:04:33,371
Let's consider a star of 10 solar masses.

63
00:04:33,586 --> 00:04:37,773
This means that this star has 
10 times the fuel available

64
00:04:37,773 --> 00:04:42,334
since the fuel is proportional 
to the mass of the star.

65
00:04:43,528 --> 00:04:46,252
However, by using the scaling law,

66
00:04:47,153 --> 00:04:50,892
and assuming an exponent <i>α</i> equal to three,

67
00:04:50,892 --> 00:04:53,754
we obtain that 
the luminosity of this star

68
00:04:53,754 --> 00:04:57,635
will be one thousand times 
the luminosity of our Sun.

69
00:04:58,092 --> 00:05:02,264
This means that this star will 
burn its fuel one thousand times

70
00:05:02,264 --> 00:05:05,034
much faster than our Sun, and therefore,

71
00:05:05,034 --> 00:05:07,690
it will live one thousand times shorter.

72
00:05:08,389 --> 00:05:11,372
In the following, we will derive 
this fundamental property

73
00:05:11,372 --> 00:05:13,320
from basic principles.

74
00:05:13,320 --> 00:05:16,944
We know from everyday experience 
that a cloud of gas

75
00:05:16,944 --> 00:05:19,956
tends to fill all available space.

76
00:05:20,348 --> 00:05:23,166
On cosmic scale, this is not true

77
00:05:23,166 --> 00:05:28,072
because of the gravitation that tends
to contract the gas under its own weight,

78
00:05:28,515 --> 00:05:31,376
heating it up eventually to a temperature

79
00:05:31,376 --> 00:05:34,983
which is high enough
to ignite nuclear fusion.

80
00:05:35,519 --> 00:05:38,695
An equilibrium is reached when 
the gravitational force

81
00:05:38,695 --> 00:05:42,403
which acts to contract the star,
and the gas pressure force

82
00:05:42,403 --> 00:05:45,946
which acts to expand the star
are balanced.

83
00:05:45,946 --> 00:05:48,838
This is the so-called 
<i>hydrostatic equilibrium</i>

84
00:05:48,838 --> 00:05:53,090
and in a nutshell the Sun is 
a gravitationally self-confined

85
00:05:53,090 --> 00:05:54,872
nuclear fusion reactor.

