00:18:19,485 --> 00:18:23,702
will be decreased by a certain fraction

245
00:18:23,987 --> 00:18:26,790
depending on the opacity of the medium.

246
00:18:27,417 --> 00:18:32,547
This fraction can be expressed as 
a function of the original intensity

247
00:18:32,547 --> 00:18:36,685
of the photon beam of the local density 
<i>ρ</i> of the medium

248
00:18:37,326 --> 00:18:39,532
and the opacity, K, of the medium.

249
00:18:40,744 --> 00:18:47,015
Which, in SI units, is measured
in square meters per kilogram.

250
00:18:47,715 --> 00:18:51,489
This means that over a distance, ds,

251
00:18:51,489 --> 00:18:57,121
sufficiently small for K ρ

252
00:18:57,121 --> 00:19:05,271
to remain constant, the number of photons 
is decreased by this factor here.

253
00:19:07,580 --> 00:19:10,076
Which are the sources of 
opacity in the Sun?

254
00:19:10,722 --> 00:19:14,285
Strictly speaking, the opacity 
is a function of the frequency

255
00:19:15,117 --> 00:19:18,592
of the electromagnetic radiation, 
and also depends on

256
00:19:18,592 --> 00:19:20,930
a multitude of atomic processes.

257
00:19:21,581 --> 00:19:25,826
In the Sun, among the different 
interactions leading to opacity,

258
00:19:25,826 --> 00:19:29,851
the most important are 
the inverse Bremsstrahlung

259
00:19:29,851 --> 00:19:32,038
or free-free absorption,

260
00:19:32,517 --> 00:19:35,702
the bound-free absorption 
or photo-ionization,

261
00:19:36,046 --> 00:19:39,521
the bound-bound absorption 
or photo-excitation.

262
00:19:39,908 --> 00:19:45,666
However, for temperatures larger 
than 10 million degrees

263
00:19:45,666 --> 00:19:49,283
the dominant process is 
Thomson scattering,

264
00:19:49,660 --> 00:19:54,924
the scattering that photons undergo 
over free electrons in the plasma.

265
00:19:55,467 --> 00:19:57,563
The Thomson scattering cross section

266
00:19:58,235 --> 00:20:02,090
is linked to the classical radius 
of the electron

267
00:20:02,090 --> 00:20:06,091
and it is extremely small,
as can be seen in this formula.

268
00:20:07,911 --> 00:20:10,631
Using the Thomson scattering 
cross section,

269
00:20:10,631 --> 00:20:14,599
we can compute the 
mean free path of photons

270
00:20:14,599 --> 00:20:20,514
to undergo Thomson scattering 
on free electrons in the Sun's interior.

271
00:20:20,951 --> 00:20:27,115
The mean free path will depend inversely 
upon the local density of the plasma

272
00:20:27,507 --> 00:20:31,033
and the Thomson scattering cross section.

273
00:20:31,364 --> 00:20:33,091
Now if we plug the numbers

274
00:20:33,988 --> 00:20:39,571
into this formula, we realize that 
the mean free path for Thomson scattering

275
00:20:39,571 --> 00:20:43,652
is extremely small,
of the order of a centimeter.

276
00:20:45,225 --> 00:20:49,298
This is much smaller than the Sun's radius

277
00:20:50,836 --> 00:20:54,771
and in this limit, the photons undergo

278
00:20:54,771 --> 00:20:58,214
many scatterings
before exiting the surface.

279
00:20:58,526 --> 00:21:02,802
We can represent this process 
as a diffusion process.

280
00:21:02,802 --> 00:21:09,431
The spreading of an ensemble of photons 
that undergo a diffusion process

281
00:21:09,985 --> 00:21:13,199
can be represented in the following way,

282
00:21:13,912 --> 00:21:17,038
where D is a diffusion coefficient.

283
00:21:17,038 --> 00:21:19,694
The diffusion coefficient can be computed

284
00:21:19,694 --> 00:21:23,625
as the ratio of the mean free path

285
00:21:23,625 --> 00:21:28,324
between two collisions,
divided by the effective time

286
00:21:28,324 --> 00:21:30,159
between these two collisions.
[τ_(between collisions)]

287
00:21:30,631 --> 00:21:35,927
If we use this formula, we can compute 
an average time that it will take

288
00:21:35,927 --> 00:21:39,779
for an ensemble of photons
to diffuse up to the surface of the Sun

289
00:21:40,400 --> 00:21:42,195
in the following way.

290
00:21:43,931 --> 00:21:51,040
The striking result is that it will take 
approximately 100 million years

291
00:21:51,760 --> 00:21:56,031
for a photon to escape from the center 
to the surface of the sun

292
00:21:56,031 --> 00:22:00,236
and this reduces dramatically 
the luminosity of the sun.

293
00:22:01,580 --> 00:22:06,874
Now going back to the luminosity, 
we can estimate it using the formulas

294
00:22:06,874 --> 00:22:09,670
and the numbers that 
we have just computed.

295
00:22:09,883 --> 00:22:13,332
If we do that, and we plug
the numbers into this formula,

296
00:22:13,332 --> 00:22:17,357
we end up with a value 
which is very close

297
00:22:17,357 --> 00:22:20,630
to the actual luminosity of the sun.

298
00:22:21,162 --> 00:22:23,607
The second important result we can obtain

299
00:22:23,607 --> 00:22:29,358
is by recalling the effective 
average temperature of the sun

300
00:22:29,358 --> 00:22:32,549
that we have estimated from 
the hydrostatic equilibrium.

301
00:22:33,088 --> 00:22:36,362
Using the expression for 
the mean free path

302
00:22:36,362 --> 00:22:40,892
for Thomson scattering, we can thus 
find a relation between

303
00:22:40,892 --> 00:22:43,996
the luminosity and the mass of the star.

304
00:22:44,326 --> 00:22:48,632
In doing this, we realize that 
the luminosity scales like

305
00:22:48,632 --> 00:22:50,867
the third power of the mass.

306
00:22:50,867 --> 00:22:55,203
This is an extremely important result 
since from basic principles

307
00:22:55,203 --> 00:22:59,864
we have now recovered a scaling low, 
which is observed in nature

308
00:22:59,864 --> 00:23:03,037
from experimental data 
for main sequence's stars.

309
00:23:04,381 --> 00:23:08,174
In this module, we have derived 
estimates of solar properties

310
00:23:08,174 --> 00:23:09,946
from basic principles.

311
00:23:10,190 --> 00:23:14,845
We have made dramatic approximations 
to shed light on basic physics.

312
00:23:15,361 --> 00:23:19,099
We have made the assumption that 
the Sun is an homogeneous ball

313
00:23:19,099 --> 00:23:22,729
of protons and electrons,
which are in hydrostatic equilibrium.

314
00:23:22,979 --> 00:23:27,789
We have also assumed 
an ideal equation of state,

315
00:23:27,789 --> 00:23:30,208
which is that of ideal gases.

316
00:23:30,208 --> 00:23:33,952
We have also made the assumption 
that the energy is transported

317
00:23:33,952 --> 00:23:35,971
solely by radiation.

318
00:23:35,971 --> 00:23:37,800
This has allowed us to compute

319
00:23:37,800 --> 00:23:40,621
some of the most fundamental
properties of the Sun

320
00:23:40,621 --> 00:23:43,898
and in general of main sequence's stars.

321
00:23:44,360 --> 00:23:46,513
However, the assumptions that we have made

322
00:23:46,965 --> 00:23:49,104
are not entirely satisfied.

323
00:23:49,104 --> 00:23:52,354
For example, the Sun contains 
other elements than hydrogen,

324
00:23:53,223 --> 00:23:55,874
and also it shows some internal structures

325
00:23:55,874 --> 00:23:58,326
and small deviation from 
the ideal gases law.

326
00:23:58,962 --> 00:24:01,916
Furthermore, the Sun has other
important elements

327
00:24:01,916 --> 00:24:04,163
that contribute to its dynamics.

328
00:24:04,163 --> 00:24:07,568
One of these elements is 
the presence of magnetic fields,

329
00:24:07,568 --> 00:24:10,350
which we will deal with 
in the following modules.
